<br />
I&#39;ve played tons of lotr, I play enough games to keep up with what is out there. There is nowhere near the interaction there is in versus. We all know that 95% of skirmishes are "ok, i match him up to him, him to him, him to him, he takes a wound, i take a wound, i take a wound". Versus is definitely set up to take more chances (flipping face down cards all game).<br />
<br />
Can you get &#39;lotrd&#39; in Versus? Hell ya, you sure can. I have been, Gabe Alonso and I joked about this at the Orlando 10k. <br />
<br />
Furthermore there are times when Versus can be plodding. Draw 2, play 1.<br />
<br />
I&#39;m saying they both have their lows. But the &#39;highs&#39; of rings were never much, most games plod along doing the same thing over and over, and it only got worse after Return of the King, not better. <br />
<br />
The thing I most liked about lotr was the storyline aspect. That was cool. But even that got watered down with all the dumb ringbound/unbound stuff and things like having Rosie Cotton as a companion.<br />
<br />
The big difference for me is the highs in Versus. Does that opponent have another cover fire? Should you take out his little sentinel first? Does he suspect you are going to beatdown + overload? What if he flips a second avalon ko-ing the first "Err, HOW MANY magnetos are in your gfaveyard, guy?"<br />
<br />
There is tons of bluffing, tons of &#39;game within a game&#39; mentality, tons of interaction. A teeny bit of story, but not much, it&#39;s the constant mental game and creative play.<br />
